1. Introduction to DNS Service

DNS (Domain Name System) is like the phonebook of the internet.
It translates human-readable domain names into IP addresses.

Why DNS is needed
Humans remember names easily (e.g., google.com)
Computers communicate using IP addresses (e.g., 142.250.183.14)

How DNS works (Basic Flow)
User enters domain in browser
Request goes to DNS resolver
Resolver checks cache
If not found → queries DNS servers
IP address is returned
Browser connects to the server

Key Components
DNS Resolver – Handles query from client
Root Name Server – Top-level DNS
TLD Server – (.com, .org, .in)
Authoritative DNS Server – Final answer provider

2. DNS Records and Zones
DNS Records

DNS records store mapping information.

Common Types of Records
Record Type	Purpose

A Record	Maps domain → IPv4 address
AAAA Record	Maps domain → IPv6 address
CNAME	Maps one domain to another
MX Record	Mail server routing
NS Record	Name servers for domain
TXT Record	Text data (verification, SPF, DKIM)
SRV Record	Service-specific records

Example:
example.com → 192.168.1.1 (A Record)
www.example.com → example.com (CNAME)
DNS Zones

A DNS Zone is a portion of DNS namespace managed by a specific organization.

Types of Zones:
Forward Lookup Zone → Domain → IP
Reverse Lookup Zone → IP → Domain
Key Points:
Each zone contains DNS records
Managed by authoritative DNS servers
Helps distribute DNS management

